                                                          VISITING DC?

                             spring time at the Capitol
     __________________________________________________________________

   Below is a list of the tours and attractions that visitors to
   Washington may be interested in seeing. In addition to the public
   tours, my office can arrange Congressional VIP tours of the White
   House, the Federal Bureau of Investigation, the Bureau of Engraving and
   Printing, the National Archives, the Kennedy Center, and the Supreme
   Court. These tours are in great demand so please give my office several
   weeks advance notice. Tour tickets can be requested by clicking here or
   by calling my Washington, D.C. office at: (202) 224-3004.
     __________________________________________________________________

PUBLIC TOURS

Bureau of Engraving and Printing

   Public tours are designed to accommodate groups of all sizes and are
   available from 9:00 a.m. until 2:00 p.m., Monday through Friday. The
   tour lasts approximately 30 minutes. No reservations or tickets are
   required during the non-peak season (October through mid-March).
   However, tickets are necessary during the peak season (late March
   through September) and may be obtained at no charge from the ticket
   kiosk on the 15th Street side of the building. Tours begin at the 14th
   and C Street, SW entrance.

Capitol Building

   Public tours are available Monday through Friday from 9:30 a.m. until
   3:45 p.m. The building itself is open daily from 9:00 a.m. until 4:30
   p.m. The tours begin at the East front steps of the Capitol, below the
   Rotunda, and across from the Supreme Court.

Federal Bureau of Investigation

   Public tours begin every 20 minutes at the E Street entrance. The
   building is open from 8:45 a.m. until 4:15 p.m. Monday through Friday.
   Tours begin on E Street between 9th and 10th Streets, NW.

Holocaust Museum

   Public tours are available daily from 10:00 a.m. until 5:30 p.m.,
   however, tickets are required and are not available through
   Congressional offices. To receive a ticket, you may wait in line at
   8:00 a.m. each morning. The ticket may be for later in the day. The Box
   Office is on the 14th Street side of the Museum and opens at 9:00 a.m.
   In addition, for a $3 service charge, you can reserve tickets in
   advance through TicketMaster. Tours begin at 100 Raoul Wallenburg
   Place, SW.

Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts

   Regular public tours are conducted by Friends of the Kennedy Center
   volunteers daily from 10:00 a.m. until 1:00 p.m. Visitors should go to
   the Tour Desk on Motor Lobby A, where tours leave approximately every
   15 minutes and last about an hour.

Library of Congress

   Tours leave from Madison Memorial Hall (101 Independence Avenue, S.E.)
   Monday through Friday at 10:00 a.m., 1:00 p.m., and 3:00 p.m. The tour
   is approximately 45 minutes in length. A slide presentation is given
   hourly beginning at 8:30 a.m.

National Archives

   Public tours are offered Monday through Friday from 10:00 a.m. through
   5:00 p.m. and are approximately 90 minutes in length. Public tours
   guests begin their tour on Constitution Avenue at 7th Street, NW.

The Pentagon

   Public tours are available Monday through Friday from 9:00 a.m. until
   3:30 p.m. and leave on the half hour. Visitors need to sign-up at the
   tour office window at the Concourse entrance of the Pentagon
   approximately 15 minutes before the tour begins. A photo ID is required
   to enter the building.

Supreme Court

   Twenty-minute courtroom lectures are available every hour on the
   half-hour when the Court is not in session, Monday through Friday from
   9:30 a.m. until 3:30 p.m. The lectures are followed by a short movie
   and exhibits. The building is open from 9:00 a.m. until 4:30 p.m. Court
   sessions begin the first Monday in October and continue two weeks per
   month through April. Visitors are allowed to listen to oral arguments.
   Courtroom seats are available to visitors on a first-come, first-served
   basis when the Court is in session from 10:00 a.m. until 12:00 noon and
   from 1:00 p.m. until 3:00 p.m. Monday through Friday. Tours begin at
   First Street and Maryland Avenue, NE.

White House

   The White House is open to the public for self-guided tours Tuesday
   through Saturday from 10:00 a.m. until 12:00 noon. Tour Officers are
   located in each room to answer any questions. Tickets are required for
   admission from mid-March through early September. Free tickets may be
   obtained from the National Park Service's White House Visitors' Center
   in the U.S. Department of Commerce Building at the corner of 15th
   Street and Pennsylvania Avenue, NW. This visitors' center is very close
   to the White House. If you have any questions about the White House
   Visitors' Center, feel free to call them at (202) 208-1631 or access
   their website by clicking here. Tickets are issued on the day of the
   tour only, on a first-come, first-served basis starting at 7:30 a.m.
   The White House Visitors Office recommends getting into line by 6:30
   a.m. or earlier during the summer months. One person may request
   tickets for up to four people. Each person √ê even babies need a ticket.
   In addition, one person in the group must have a hand stamped for
   validation. That person must be with the group of (up to four) ticket
   holders. The number of tickets for each day is limited. Each ticket
   shows when and where the tour begins. Tickets are only honored for 15
   minutes past the printed time. During the times of the year when
   tickets are not required, a first-come, first-served line forms at the
   southeast gate, which is at East Executive Avenue and E Street, for the
   10:00 a.m. until 12:00 noon self-guided public tours. National Park
   Service personnel are available to assist visitors with directions and
   questions. On occasion, the White House may be closed for an official
   event. Please check the Visitors Office 24-hour recording at
   202-456-7041 for any changes.
